To elaborate further: https://github.com/aldryn/aldryn-newsblog/blob/master/aldryn_newsblog/boilerplates/bootstrap3/templates/aldryn_newsblog/base.html#L3 is the standard template. If you want meta integration you just adapt the base.html template to look like:

```
{% block meta_tags %}
    {{ block.super }}
    {% block newsblog_meta_tags %}{% endblock %}
{% endblock %}
{% block content %}{% endblock content %}
```

and the article_detail.html just provides the facilities to overwrite it:

```
{% block newsblog_meta_tags %}
    {% if meta %}
        {% include "aldryn_newsblog/includes/meta.html" with meta=meta %}
    {% endif %}
{% endif %}
```

@petrjasek I'm not sure what you mean with auth token, the requesting entity (wufoo) will not provide it. By "more efficient way", I mean that if somebody really want to do a DoS, he'll better go with a DDoS tool like LOIC than guessing a specific url (which is not supposed to be public, even if for NTB it's currently hardcoded) to trigger ingestion.

The issue by using handshake or other shared secret is that it is vendor specific and not generic anymore. A hidden URL is a kind of shared secret anyway (we can autogenerate a key in the URL). An yes HTTPS is needed.

Maybe we can talk about this during the scrum?

Adding on, the kill kernel action will end up triggering the `killKernelEpic` from `packages/core/src/epics/websocket-kernel.js` (see
 https://github.com/nteract/nteract/blob/master/packages/core/src/epics/websocket-kernel.js#L297-L310)

I'd probably make the callback to the `concatMap` here use the `sessions` API directly

```js
const state = store.getState();
const kernel = selectors.kernel(state, { kernelRef: action.payload.kernelRef })

return sessions.destroy(serverConfig, kernel.sessionId).pipe(
  map(() => {
    window.close();
    return actions.killKernelSuccessful({
      kernelRef: action.payload.kernelRef
    });
  }),
  catchError(err => {
    // Not sure if we want to error here or just close anyways
    window.close();
    return of(
      actions.killKernelFailed({
        error: err,
        kernelRef: action.payload.kernelRef
      })
    );
  })
);

```

In an earlier comment, you asked about the meaning of the `attrs_iter` ("an iterable of attributes") variable. It's used by the parent class, `_BaseTestCase`, in its `tearDownClass` method:

```python
    @classmethod
    def tearDownClass(cls):
        """Delete created resources."""
        for attrs in cls.attrs_iter:
            delete(cls.cfg, attrs['_href'])
```

