@robertnishihara @pcmoritz @stephanie-wang Ah, yeah, you can't assign to an object that isn't constructed. What you need is a "placement new" operator, i.e. to construct an object in existing memory. The syntax is
```
void *address = malloc(sizeof(T));
T *ptr = new(address) T(...);
// ...
ptr->~T();
free(address);
```
Normally you should avoid that operator when possible, but this is one of the very rare instances where you can (indeed, must) use that operator. :)

Oh, and by the way, in cases where you _do_ need to be assigning, you don't need `empty_execution_dependencies`. It doesn't save you any efficiency. There's no heap allocation for an empty vector, so you should just do `execution_dependencies.clear()` or `execution_dependencies = std::vector<ObjectID>()` (if you want the capacity to remain the same), or `std::vector<ObjectID>().swap(execution_dependencies)` (if you want the underlying memory to be freed).

